{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519968"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:18:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:18:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13121"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13121"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.12,0.01,0.01,0.69]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5558"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91458"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5558"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13121"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75123"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"759"},{"type":"tags","id":"1179"},{"type":"tags","id":"1638"},{"type":"tags","id":"2136"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9417"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11358"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14882"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31242"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42849"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44538"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91458"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents with a one day history of a painful bulge in her right groin. She has been aware of a swelling in that region which has gradually increased in size over the past several months. Until recently the lump would disappear when she lay down, but now it is present all the time. She was getting intermittent episodes of discomfort at the site of the bulge, especially after prolonged standing or physical activity. She has no other symptoms and is otherwise in good health\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination the patient is in obvious distress. Her blood pressure is 115/65 mmH, pulse 90/min and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft and the only abnormal finding is a palpable tender mass is felt below the inguinal ligament, medial to the femoral pulse. The mass is non-reducible. There are no signs of skin changes or overlying erythema. No other abnormalities are found on examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound","CT scan abdomen and pelvis","Antibiotics and leg elevation","Fine needle aspiration for cytology","Immediate surgical repair"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe two important causes of groin swellings are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ehernia (inguinal, femoral)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Elymph nodes (infection, neoplasia)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an incarcerated and possibly strangulated femoral hernia. If it was not painful and tender, the hernia could be managed at leisure. However these symptoms imply that the contents of the hernia (typically small bowel) have become ischaemic and if any decision-making is delayed, perforation may occur. This patient needs an immediate \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical repair\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst patients with incarcerated groin hernias often have clinical evidence of small bowel obstruction, this is often not the case with femoral hernia. The hernia neck is small and it tends to be only a part of the wall of the bowel that gets trapped in the hernia -  a Richter hernia (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst an \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E can be considered as part of the diagnostic process, in this case the diagnosis is clear on clinical assessment alone and any form of imaging is superfluous and will not add any helpful information. Similarly a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E will not help and may only delay surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the underlying process was that of lymph node inflammation and infection, then it is likely that the patient would have symptoms from the draining areas (eg cellulitis of the leg) and there would be several enlarged tender swelling in the groin. In those circumstances, \u003Cstrong\u003Eantibiotics and leg elevation\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA painless and non-tender swelling might raise the possibilities of neoplasia and in such circumstances a \u003Cstrong\u003Efine needle aspiration for cytology\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered, but that is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Femoral hernias have a higher risk of strangulation compared to other hernia types"],"references":["Hamilton W, Pascoe J, John J, et al. Diagnosing groin lumps. BMJ 2021; 372:n578."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75123"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13121"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20589"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20589"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/qhDiRWeTYrNbgeKjndwgnFnEhwXCvs.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/qhDiRWe